00:40.781 --> 00:44.710
Murdoch Mysteries S02E12

01:22.381 --> 01:24.422
Who's there?!

01:25.061 --> 01:28.062
Answer me,
or I'm setting the dogs on you!

01:29.340 --> 01:31.902
God help you!
Go!

01:58.021 --> 02:00.021
Look at the moon.
It's so big.

02:00.221 --> 02:01.621
Yes, it's beautiful.

02:01.821 --> 02:03.861
Do you think there's moon men
living up there?

02:04.060 --> 02:05.381
Oh, I don't think so, Alwyn.

02:05.580 --> 02:07.021
The moon has no atmosphere.

02:07.220 --> 02:09.741
And life needs free oxygen
to survive.

02:09.940 --> 02:11.181
William?

02:12.741 --> 02:14.341
How surprising to see you here.

02:14.541 --> 02:15.820
And Mrs. Jones.

02:16.020 --> 02:16.860
Dr. Ogden.

02:17.060 --> 02:18.461
Out gazing at the moon,
were you?

02:18.661 --> 02:20.740
Mr. Murdoch says
life can't exist up there

02:20.941 --> 02:22.741
'cause there's no oxygen.

02:22.941 --> 02:24.900
Well, actually, they've
just discovered a bacterium

02:25.101 --> 02:27.461
that thrives in
the complete absence of oxygen.

02:27.661 --> 02:29.740
Why, then, I would bet
that there are moon men

02:29.941 --> 02:32.620
up there right now
eating all that green cheese.

02:36.420 --> 02:38.340
I'm sorry.
My manners.

02:38.541 --> 02:40.621
I'd like you to meet
Reginald Poundsett.

02:40.820 --> 02:43.540
- This is William --
- Detective William Murdoch.

02:43.740 --> 02:44.381
A pleasure.

02:44.581 --> 02:47.140
- And Mrs. Enid Jones.
- Enid Jones.

02:47.340 --> 02:48.380
Mrs. Jones.

02:49.340 --> 02:50.180
And I'm Alwyn.

02:50.380 --> 02:51.861
Young man.

02:53.820 --> 02:55.940
Well, we should be going.
We don't want to be late.

02:56.139 --> 02:58.741
Yes.
Have a wonderful evening.

03:02.701 --> 03:05.060
So there could be moon men?

03:05.260 --> 03:05.900
Well...

03:06.100 --> 03:08.779
Yes, Alwyn.
Of course there could.

03:09.540 --> 03:11.260
Of course there could be.

03:17.500 --> 03:19.100
He's asleep.

03:20.500 --> 03:22.060
Dreaming of moon men, no doubt.

03:29.940 --> 03:33.700
It was strange bumping into
Dr. Ogden like that, wasn't it?

03:34.420 --> 03:35.540
Yes.

03:39.460 --> 03:42.700
Mr. Poundsett seems like
a pleasant fellow.

03:44.019 --> 03:46.939
So, is it a romance
between them, then?

03:47.140 --> 03:48.140
I wouldn't know.

03:48.340 --> 03:50.539
We don't discuss such things.

03:52.860 --> 03:54.739
Would it bother you if it was?

03:55.979 --> 03:59.060
I-I don't know.

03:59.259 --> 04:00.979
Why would you ask me
such a thing?

04:01.180 --> 04:04.298
It's obvious when you see her, William.

04:04.500 --> 04:06.740
Obvious to me, if not to you.

04:07.338 --> 04:09.939
Enid, I can assure you
that Dr. Ogden and I

04:10.139 --> 04:12.939
are professional colleagues,
and that is all.

04:13.139 --> 04:14.740
Are you sure
you're not just saying that

04:14.940 --> 04:16.099
to spare my feelings?

04:19.019 --> 04:22.219
Sorry to interrupt, sir.
Uh, ma'am.

04:23.019 --> 04:24.500
You're needed, sir.

04:33.220 --> 04:35.139
- Evening, sir.
- What have we?

04:35.339 --> 04:37.459
The victim was found
just after 9:30.

04:37.659 --> 04:38.660
Have you determined identity?

04:38.859 --> 04:40.658
We found this on his person.
Merrill Hardy.

04:40.859 --> 04:43.538
He was vice president
at Dominion Bank.

04:44.179 --> 04:45.059
What are those?

04:45.259 --> 04:47.459
Those, sir, we believe,
are his dogs.

04:47.659 --> 04:50.538
And they --
Well, they've been mauled.

04:50.739 --> 04:53.738
Strange place for a banker
to be walking his dogs.

04:53.939 --> 04:54.939
I thought so, too.

04:59.739 --> 05:01.979
Hello again, Doctor.
What have we?

05:02.178 --> 05:03.379
Quite a mess.

05:03.578 --> 05:05.819
The entire throat area
is torn open.

05:06.019 --> 05:07.618
Torn?

05:07.818 --> 05:09.379
It appears to be
the result of a bite,

05:09.579 --> 05:12.219
but I have no idea what could cause
such a savage wound.

05:12.419 --> 05:14.659
Perhaps his dogs turned on him?

05:15.258 --> 05:16.539
Except they're both dead.

05:16.738 --> 05:19.619
And this is much larger
than anything a dog could do.

05:19.818 --> 05:21.899
It could be a bear, I suppose.

05:22.099 --> 05:24.458
Bears use their claws.

05:25.019 --> 05:26.939
A wolf, perhaps?

05:27.138 --> 05:27.939
Possibly.

05:28.139 --> 05:29.938
But a wolf running loose
in a modern city?

05:30.139 --> 05:32.739
It's like some terrible
fairy tale.

05:32.939 --> 05:33.938
Yes.

05:34.137 --> 05:36.139
Fairy tales are make-believe.

05:37.737 --> 05:41.539
And what we have here
is very, very real.

05:49.658 --> 05:52.098
Yes.
Shocking is the word.

05:52.298 --> 05:53.538
No. No. Of course.
You're right, sir.

05:53.738 --> 05:55.379
There are no words.

05:55.579 --> 05:57.818
I'll see to it personally.
Bye.

05:58.339 --> 05:59.938
- The chief constable?
- The bleeding mayor.

06:00.139 --> 06:02.578
Seems him and Merrill Hardy
were tennis partners.

06:02.779 --> 06:04.538
Naturally, he wants this beast
captured and killed.

06:04.739 --> 06:06.058
- Of course.
- So I've called in a tracker.

06:06.258 --> 06:07.898
We've got one, you know.
Works at the stables.

06:08.459 --> 06:10.337
Oh.
That's prudent, I suppose.

06:10.538 --> 06:13.019
But I'm not entirely convinced
we're looking for a wolf.

06:13.218 --> 06:13.897
Why not?

06:14.097 --> 06:16.138
Well, there are a number
of troubling questions.

06:16.338 --> 06:17.338
Such as?

06:17.538 --> 06:20.138
When was the last time
you heard of a wolf attack?

06:20.338 --> 06:22.538
I don't know,
but I know they happen.

06:22.739 --> 06:24.578
They're what make
the Brothers Grimm so bloody grim.

06:24.777 --> 06:27.098
Yes, but wouldn't the wolf
have fed on the carcass?

06:27.937 --> 06:29.058
Perhaps it was scared off.

06:30.018 --> 06:31.418
There's also this.

06:32.538 --> 06:33.817
Mr. Hardy's gun.

06:34.018 --> 06:37.137
He had it out and ready
when he was killed.

06:37.338 --> 06:38.137
Still loaded.

06:38.338 --> 06:40.338
As if he never had a chance
to get a shot off.

06:40.538 --> 06:43.537
I admit, that is curious.

06:44.138 --> 06:47.017
Excuse me, Inspector.
Uh, you asked for a tracker?

06:47.218 --> 06:48.258
Ah. James, isn't it?
Come in.

06:48.458 --> 06:49.378
Crabtree!

06:49.938 --> 06:51.738
Jimmy, actually.
Jimmy McLeod.

06:51.938 --> 06:53.738
Detective William Murdoch.
Nice to meet you, Jimmy.

06:53.938 --> 06:55.617
- The same.
- Sir?

06:55.818 --> 06:57.537
Take Jimmy here
back to the murder scene.

06:57.738 --> 06:59.217
See if he can pick up
the trail of this wolf.

06:59.418 --> 07:00.617
Yes, sir.

07:03.418 --> 07:06.338
So now the investigation
is officially under way,

07:06.538 --> 07:08.817
how are we gonna answer
these lingering questions?

07:09.018 --> 07:12.299
By finding out what a banker was doing
in a burned-out foundry

07:12.498 --> 07:15.178
with a loaded gun
and two guard dogs.

07:18.298 --> 07:21.137
I don't know
what Merrill was doing there.

07:21.738 --> 07:23.297
He just said, "I'm...

07:23.497 --> 07:26.537
I'm taking the dogs,
and I'll be back in an hour."

07:27.657 --> 07:29.337
And then he kissed me.

07:31.738 --> 07:34.817
If I had known it was
going to be the last time...

07:36.257 --> 07:39.937
Mrs. Hardy, this must be
terribly difficult for you.

07:40.937 --> 07:44.336
Your husband was carrying
a pistol.

07:45.618 --> 07:47.537
A pistol?

07:48.777 --> 07:50.297
What on earth for?
What...

07:50.497 --> 07:52.698
Perhaps he was having trouble
with someone?

07:53.616 --> 07:55.058
Oh, no, no, no.

07:55.817 --> 07:58.016
Merrill got along
with everybody.

07:58.216 --> 08:01.297
Yet he felt the need to keep
two large guard dogs as well.

08:01.497 --> 08:04.137
We only got those last month.

08:04.856 --> 08:08.096
Merrill said there had been some lurkers
in the neighborhood.

08:09.537 --> 08:11.496
But now I'm wondering
if it was something else.

08:12.697 --> 08:14.176
What do you mean?

08:14.736 --> 08:16.737
One night I woke,
and he was standing there,

08:16.936 --> 08:21.777
staring out the window,
as if he was looking for someone...

08:21.977 --> 08:23.817
or something.

08:26.017 --> 08:28.538
Mrs. Hardy,
did your husband keep a diary

08:28.737 --> 08:31.656
or some place
he collected his thoughts?

08:31.858 --> 08:33.897
He had a daybook in his desk.

08:34.936 --> 08:36.577
Concrete.

08:36.777 --> 08:39.337
Not many tracks to be found
in concrete.

08:39.537 --> 08:40.496
No.

08:41.216 --> 08:43.655
So, how does one track
when there are no tracks?

08:43.856 --> 08:48.055
Do you look for overturned stones,
broken twigs, and such?

08:48.256 --> 08:49.897
Well, there's always tracks.

08:50.097 --> 08:53.136
You don't have to find every one.
Just the next one.

08:53.336 --> 08:55.537
Where did you learn to track?

08:55.737 --> 08:56.656
My grandfather.

08:56.856 --> 08:59.137
I lived with him
until I was 10.

08:59.337 --> 09:01.057
Where did you go then?

09:01.255 --> 09:05.056
I got taken away.
Sent to residential school.

09:08.216 --> 09:09.697
What is it?

09:10.456 --> 09:12.297
See for yourself.

09:12.496 --> 09:15.176
These are a man's footprints.
We're looking for a wolf.

09:15.376 --> 09:18.897
But look how he was standing.
Facing the wall.

09:20.376 --> 09:22.417
Or...

09:22.616 --> 09:24.736
peering around the wall.

09:25.936 --> 09:28.496
He may have watched the attack.

09:28.696 --> 09:31.376
In fact,
this man could be involved.

09:31.576 --> 09:32.616
Maybe.

09:32.816 --> 09:33.936
Maybe not.

09:34.135 --> 09:35.737
What makes you say that?

09:36.896 --> 09:39.576
Because now the tracks
go the other way.

09:40.296 --> 09:42.176
And he was running.

09:43.136 --> 09:45.497
Well, yes. He was fleeing
the scene of the crime.

09:46.137 --> 09:48.295
Or racing for his life.

10:05.696 --> 10:09.135
Mrs. Hardy,
do you know a Jake S.?

10:09.935 --> 10:11.855
Only one.
Jacob Summers.

10:12.056 --> 10:15.416
He's an architect,
an associate of Merrill's.

10:18.415 --> 10:19.815
Pull!

10:22.496 --> 10:23.575
Damn!

10:23.775 --> 10:25.015
Jacob Summers.

10:26.696 --> 10:27.255
Yes?

10:27.455 --> 10:30.136
Detective William Murdoch,
Toronto Constabulary.

10:31.416 --> 10:33.135
Well, we'll talk tomorrow.

10:34.095 --> 10:35.456
Detective.

10:36.215 --> 10:37.455
How may I help you?

10:37.655 --> 10:40.456
I understand
you knew Merrill Hardy?

10:40.654 --> 10:42.616
Yes, I did.

10:42.816 --> 10:44.576
Terrible what happened.

10:44.775 --> 10:46.936
Did you send him this telegram?

10:49.535 --> 10:52.015
Jamison Foundry.
That's where Merrill was killed.

10:52.216 --> 10:53.295
Are you suggesting
I had something to do with it?

10:53.496 --> 10:55.295
I repeat, sir --
Did you send him this telegram?

10:55.495 --> 10:56.855
No, I didn't.

10:57.056 --> 10:59.935
Curious. He apparently only knew
one Jake S. -- you.

11:00.135 --> 11:02.855
I sign all my correspondence
"J. Summers."

11:03.056 --> 11:03.935
Everyone knows that.

11:04.135 --> 11:06.175
- Including Merrill Hardy?
- Well, I should think so.

11:06.376 --> 11:07.775
We did business
on several occasions.

11:07.974 --> 11:09.335
I'll need to know
your whereabouts

11:09.535 --> 11:10.855
for yesterday afternoon
and evening.

11:11.055 --> 11:12.335
Detective, I am not this Jake S.

11:12.535 --> 11:15.415
Again, sir.
Your whereabouts.

11:15.615 --> 11:17.095
I was at the office until 6:00,

11:17.294 --> 11:18.494
and then I went
to the Waverly Men's Club,

11:18.694 --> 11:19.935
where I spent the remainder
of the evening.

11:20.135 --> 11:21.574
Pull!

11:26.695 --> 11:29.055
Where the devil is he headed?

11:31.095 --> 11:32.134
Shh.

11:35.975 --> 11:38.814
Stay behind me.
This could be dangerous.

11:44.734 --> 11:46.215
Doesn't seem
all that dangerous to me.

11:50.095 --> 11:51.454
- Oh!
- Rise and shine.

11:56.695 --> 11:57.934
This telegram
Merrill Hardy received

11:58.134 --> 12:00.135
was sent while Mr. Summers
was at his club.

12:00.334 --> 12:01.135
And we're sure of that?

12:01.335 --> 12:02.735
Several people
have placed him there.

12:02.934 --> 12:04.494
He could have got someone
to send it for him.

12:04.695 --> 12:07.334
Perhaps. But there is
the issue of his signature.

12:07.534 --> 12:09.415
Perhaps he slipped up
and signed it differently.

12:09.615 --> 12:11.814
Or perhaps
he's telling the truth,

12:12.014 --> 12:13.934
and it's the killer
who has slipped up.

12:14.135 --> 12:15.014
So Hardy gets the telegram

12:15.215 --> 12:17.334
and realizes he's being lured
to this location.

12:17.534 --> 12:18.934
So why not go to the police?

12:19.135 --> 12:20.534
I think we should assume
that Mr. Hardy

12:20.734 --> 12:21.894
was involved
in something criminal.

12:22.094 --> 12:23.934
So, thinking he has
the advantage,

12:24.135 --> 12:25.254
he prepares for a confrontation.

12:25.453 --> 12:28.214
Only two dogs and a gun
aren't enough to stop the killer.

12:29.294 --> 12:31.734
Excuse me, sir.
We've had a spot of success.

12:31.934 --> 12:33.455
You've tracked down a wolf?

12:35.053 --> 12:36.335
Not a wolf.

12:36.534 --> 12:39.535
I was a mite dry,
and was a fella I know

12:39.734 --> 12:42.614
keeps a stash
'round back of the boiler,

12:42.814 --> 12:46.534
on account of his missus gets into it
if it's in the house.

12:46.735 --> 12:48.733
So you thought
you'd help yourself?

12:48.933 --> 12:50.254
I was just borrowing.

12:50.454 --> 12:51.973
I'm not a thief.

12:52.173 --> 12:53.734
Of course not.

12:53.934 --> 12:54.974
So, what happened?

12:56.334 --> 12:57.813
I heard 'em.

12:58.014 --> 13:01.253
Dogs growling as if they were fighting
for their lives.

13:02.534 --> 13:04.014
So you went to see
what was happening.

13:04.214 --> 13:05.093
Aye.

13:05.293 --> 13:07.574
Saw the dogs lying there.

13:08.534 --> 13:09.814
Torn to pieces!

13:11.174 --> 13:12.734
And then I saw it.

13:12.934 --> 13:14.095
Saw what?

13:15.493 --> 13:19.052
- A flash of fur.
- A wolf, perhaps?

13:19.254 --> 13:21.574
Aye.
That's what it was, all right.

13:21.774 --> 13:22.414
A wolf.

13:22.614 --> 13:24.933
Mm. And did you see
what happened to the victim?

13:25.133 --> 13:26.734
No.

13:26.934 --> 13:28.333
But I heard him scream.

13:29.214 --> 13:30.654
And then I ran.
And I hid.

13:30.853 --> 13:32.773
Like a coward.

13:33.213 --> 13:35.413
And then I saw it walk past.

13:35.614 --> 13:36.733
The wolf?

13:36.933 --> 13:38.853
It weren't no wolf.

13:39.053 --> 13:40.174
It was a man.

13:40.374 --> 13:42.333
You said you saw a wolf.
Now, which was it?

13:42.534 --> 13:43.893
You ain't listening.

13:44.453 --> 13:46.734
It was a wolf I saw
in that building,

13:46.933 --> 13:48.853
but it was a man that came out!

13:52.694 --> 13:54.334
I think we can all agree

13:54.534 --> 13:57.093
that the witness was describing
a werewolf.

13:57.294 --> 13:59.614
Bloody hell, Crabtree.
It wasn't a werewolf.

13:59.813 --> 14:01.253
It was a full moon
last night, sir.

14:01.453 --> 14:02.974
There was a man,
and there was a wolf.

14:03.174 --> 14:05.453
And the man was using his wolf
as a weapon.

14:05.653 --> 14:07.333
But, sir, the witness
only saw the one leave.

14:07.534 --> 14:08.892
He was three sheets to the wind
in a gale.

14:09.092 --> 14:10.574
Who knows what he saw?

14:11.134 --> 14:13.813
Sir, it's probably not my place
to say this.

14:14.013 --> 14:15.733
Speak your mind, Jimmy.

14:15.934 --> 14:18.012
Well, sir, uh,
it's my understanding

14:18.213 --> 14:21.533
that the witness didn't say
he saw a wolf exactly.

14:21.733 --> 14:22.893
Just a flash.

14:23.093 --> 14:24.253
It was the sounds
that he heard --

14:24.453 --> 14:25.973
the snarling and the growling --

14:26.174 --> 14:27.612
that made him think
it was a wolf.

14:27.813 --> 14:29.614
So what do you think it was?

14:29.813 --> 14:31.492
A windigo, sir.

14:32.172 --> 14:32.814
A windigo?

14:33.013 --> 14:34.533
It's the name that we give
to an evil spirit

14:34.734 --> 14:36.133
that lives up
in the northern woods.

14:36.333 --> 14:37.333
It takes possession
of the people

14:37.533 --> 14:39.654
and makes them hunger
for human flesh.

14:39.853 --> 14:41.892
Cannibals.
Now, that's a chilling thought.

14:42.093 --> 14:44.133
You know, I've heard that
in the islands near Borneo --

14:44.334 --> 14:45.852
- Crabtree!
- Actually, sir,

14:46.053 --> 14:47.333
there may be something
to both of these arguments.

14:47.533 --> 14:49.132
Oh, not you too, Murdoch.

14:49.332 --> 14:51.332
I'm not suggesting
anything supernatural,

14:51.533 --> 14:54.893
but there are people who believe
themselves to be animals.

14:55.092 --> 14:57.053
So you're saying
this is some kind of lunatic

14:57.253 --> 14:58.332
with a taste for human blood?

14:58.532 --> 15:00.693
It would explain
the feral nature of the attacks.

15:00.893 --> 15:03.292
How does a man tear out
another man's throat, then?

15:03.493 --> 15:05.332
And what kind of lunatic
has the presence of mind

15:05.532 --> 15:07.812
to send his victim a telegram
in advance?

15:08.012 --> 15:09.493
That's what I intend
to find out.

15:09.693 --> 15:11.053
Oh, fine.
You go looking for your wolf man.

15:11.253 --> 15:13.053
And you two get back
to the alley.

15:13.253 --> 15:14.773
We're looking for a man
and a wolf.

15:14.972 --> 15:16.652
See if you can find out
where they went.

15:18.172 --> 15:19.132
Well, move it!

15:20.732 --> 15:22.572
So, have you
an opinion, Dr. Roberts?

15:22.773 --> 15:26.133
The condition you're describing
is lycanthropy.

15:26.332 --> 15:28.452
The term is applied
to individuals

15:28.652 --> 15:30.332
who, for psychological reasons,

15:30.532 --> 15:33.693
believe themselves to be
an animal, most often a wolf.

15:33.893 --> 15:36.492
Hence, lycanthropy's
traditional association

15:36.693 --> 15:38.053
with the werewolf myth.

15:38.252 --> 15:40.772
The victim was discovered
with his throat ripped out.

15:40.973 --> 15:43.532
A witness claims to have heard
snarling and growling

15:43.732 --> 15:44.612
during the attacks.

15:44.812 --> 15:46.293
And you'd like to know
if this could be the work...

15:46.492 --> 15:48.131
- ...of a lycanthrope.
- Yes.

15:48.332 --> 15:50.533
There are several
documented instances

15:50.732 --> 15:52.411
of lycanthropes attacking sheep

15:52.612 --> 15:54.492
because they're the natural prey
of the wolf.

15:54.692 --> 15:55.732
Well, this would seem to suggest

15:55.931 --> 15:59.613
the sufferer
was extremely delusional.

15:59.812 --> 16:03.612
It's a very rare
and a very strange condition.

16:03.812 --> 16:06.212
In this case, the killer
seems to have been lucid enough

16:06.412 --> 16:08.932
to have lured his victim
to his death.

16:09.532 --> 16:12.131
There is precedent
for such behavior.

