led a woman into a cave,

16:18.132 --> 16:21.212
where he subsequently killed
and devoured her.

16:21.412 --> 16:23.652
So, could your killer
be a lycanthrope?

16:23.853 --> 16:24.731
Absolutely.

16:24.931 --> 16:25.932
Is he one?

16:26.131 --> 16:28.092
I couldn't say
without examining him.

16:28.292 --> 16:30.132
But what I can tell you
with authority is

16:30.332 --> 16:34.852
that you're dealing with
a deeply disturbed individual.

16:38.491 --> 16:40.572
I've never ridden
in a carriage before.

16:40.771 --> 16:42.531
- Really?
- Yeah.

16:42.731 --> 16:45.451
I've cleaned them,
I've harnessed horses to them,

16:45.652 --> 16:47.612
but I've never rode in one.

16:48.931 --> 16:51.091
How did you come to work
at the stable?

16:51.291 --> 16:53.772
I wanted to be a copper,
but it didn't work out.

16:53.972 --> 16:55.890
I think you'd make
a fine copper.

16:56.091 --> 16:58.452
Your instincts are sound.

16:59.371 --> 17:02.491
Well, we both know
there aren't any Indian coppers.

17:04.252 --> 17:06.211
Doesn't mean there couldn't be.

17:09.771 --> 17:12.611
They tried to beat the Indian out of me
at the school.

17:12.810 --> 17:15.329
They should have beat
the color off of me, too.

17:16.251 --> 17:18.132
It'll be a long time
before they let someone like me

17:18.330 --> 17:20.050
wear that uniform.

17:27.131 --> 17:29.291
Detective,
your timing is impeccable.

17:29.490 --> 17:32.451
I was just about to leave
for an engagement with Mr. Poundsett.

17:32.650 --> 17:34.652
I see.
Well, then I'll be brief.

17:34.851 --> 17:36.531
Have you Mr. Hardy's
postmortem results?

17:36.731 --> 17:38.971
I do.
Nothing beyond the obvious.

17:39.171 --> 17:40.532
Death due to massive blood loss.

17:40.731 --> 17:43.331
Jugular and carotid arteries
both severed.

17:43.532 --> 17:45.930
Do you think it's possible
the wound could have been caused

17:46.130 --> 17:47.531
by sharpened fingernails?

17:47.731 --> 17:48.531
Fingernails?

17:48.731 --> 17:50.211
Part of a theory I'm developing,

17:50.411 --> 17:52.051
that the killer is suffering
from lycanthropy.

17:52.250 --> 17:54.651
And they're somehow emulating
the attack of a wolf?

17:54.850 --> 17:56.130
Exactly.

17:56.732 --> 17:58.850
Well, I suppose it...

17:59.050 --> 18:02.091
it might account
for the width of the gash.

18:02.291 --> 18:03.211
- But...
- But?

18:05.091 --> 18:06.290
The wound is symmetrical.

18:06.491 --> 18:07.811
A hand is not.

18:08.010 --> 18:09.330
There's only one opposing thumb.

18:09.530 --> 18:11.771
I'm also not sure
that fingernails could withstand

18:11.970 --> 18:13.731
the force required
to tear the flesh out.

18:13.931 --> 18:15.290
I see.

18:15.771 --> 18:16.572
Well, thank you.

18:16.771 --> 18:18.970
There is one other thing.

18:19.851 --> 18:23.050
Animal attacks are rare,
so I contacted some colleagues

18:23.251 --> 18:24.610
to see if they'd had
any experience with them.

18:24.811 --> 18:26.611
- And had they?
- Yes.

18:26.810 --> 18:28.330
Three, actually.
All in the last few months.

18:28.531 --> 18:30.171
I don't know
if there's any connection.

18:30.371 --> 18:32.490
Most interesting.
I'll be sure to look into it.

18:32.690 --> 18:33.851
Thank you very much, Doctor.

18:34.050 --> 18:34.931
Yes.

18:35.130 --> 18:38.931
Well, as I said, I have --
have an appointment.

18:39.130 --> 18:40.930
I have one of my own.

18:49.530 --> 18:51.410
I'm no expert, by any means,

18:51.610 --> 18:55.930
but I believe the werewolf curse
is caused by a Gypsy spell.

18:56.129 --> 18:57.211
The evil eye.

18:57.411 --> 18:58.850
Why the full moon?

18:59.050 --> 18:59.849
I don't know.

19:00.051 --> 19:02.690
I suppose it exerts
some sort of supernatural force.

19:02.889 --> 19:05.290
And after he kills,
does he turn back to human?

19:05.490 --> 19:06.290
I believe so.

19:06.490 --> 19:09.169
And with no recollection
of anything that's happened.

19:09.370 --> 19:11.450
What happens to his clothes
after he transforms?

19:11.649 --> 19:13.330
- Does he wake up naked?
- Does he wake up naked?

19:13.531 --> 19:16.289
I've often asked myself
that very question.

19:16.489 --> 19:18.330
Hmm.

19:19.770 --> 19:20.730
What is it?

19:20.930 --> 19:21.850
More shoe prints.

19:22.049 --> 19:22.930
The witness's.

19:23.130 --> 19:24.170
No.
These are different.

19:24.371 --> 19:26.130
The man the witness saw.

19:26.329 --> 19:27.730
Any wolf tracks?

19:30.130 --> 19:31.529
None.

19:32.090 --> 19:33.411
Well, we'd best see
where these lead.

19:41.410 --> 19:43.650
Enid, I must apologize to you.

19:43.850 --> 19:46.130
This case has been monopolizing my time.

19:46.329 --> 19:48.049
It's what you do.

19:48.249 --> 19:49.769
It is.

19:49.969 --> 19:51.929
However, I wanted to discuss

19:52.129 --> 19:55.929
what you brought up last night
about Dr. Ogden.

19:56.130 --> 19:57.930
And?

19:59.009 --> 20:00.530
And...

20:00.730 --> 20:03.810
I must confess
it has been difficult

20:04.010 --> 20:06.289
to put her out of my mind.

20:07.169 --> 20:08.530
I see.

20:08.729 --> 20:11.369
But I shall endeavor to do so.

20:12.289 --> 20:14.529
William, that's not enough.

20:14.729 --> 20:17.609
I don't know what more I can do.

20:17.810 --> 20:19.609
If it were just me,
I might be inclined

20:19.808 --> 20:22.609
to participate in some battle
for your affection.

20:22.809 --> 20:24.489
But there is no one else.

20:24.689 --> 20:27.730
William, of course there is.

20:27.930 --> 20:29.128
Alwyn.

20:29.329 --> 20:32.728
And as you know, he is
the most important thing in my life.

20:32.929 --> 20:37.649
I can't allow him
to grow attached to you...

20:37.849 --> 20:40.369
only to have you go back to her.

20:41.728 --> 20:42.929
I can't take that chance.

20:44.689 --> 20:46.328
Nor would I want you to.

20:47.249 --> 20:49.049
Then I need you to decide,
once and for all,

20:49.249 --> 20:51.328
what it is that you want.

21:03.610 --> 21:04.969
Where was he headed?
For the river?

21:05.169 --> 21:06.969
He wasn't going to the river.

21:08.050 --> 21:09.848
He went in there.

21:23.849 --> 21:25.409
Are you sure he came this way?

21:25.609 --> 21:27.089
Yes.

21:27.889 --> 21:28.729
No.

21:28.928 --> 21:31.049
There's been too much water.

21:31.248 --> 21:33.528
Well, if we've lost the trail,
he could be anywhere.

21:33.729 --> 21:35.729
Or he could be
up around the next bend.

21:36.528 --> 21:38.648
I think it prudent
we pay a visit to the station,

21:38.849 --> 21:39.969
report our findings,

21:40.168 --> 21:41.848
maybe enlist some help
while we're there.

21:42.049 --> 21:43.729
A search party would be good.

21:43.929 --> 21:45.968
Or maybe a trip to the armory.

21:46.168 --> 21:48.089
That'd be good, too.

22:04.809 --> 22:05.968
Used the sewers, did he?

22:06.168 --> 22:08.488
Good way to move a wolf unseen
through a city.

22:08.688 --> 22:11.689
Well, actually, sir,
we didn't find any wolf tracks.

22:12.328 --> 22:13.128
- None at all?
- No.

22:13.328 --> 22:15.529
We looked very carefully.
Your man would've found them.

22:15.728 --> 22:17.328
That's very strange.

22:17.528 --> 22:18.728
And the man you were tracking?

22:18.928 --> 22:20.689
We lost his trail in the sewer.

22:20.888 --> 22:23.128
Too much water.
Sorry, sir.

22:23.328 --> 22:24.249
Is there anything else?

22:24.448 --> 22:25.528
No.
That's good work, Jimmy.

22:25.727 --> 22:27.488
If we need you,
we'll send for you.

22:27.688 --> 22:28.969
Uh, sir, can I have a moment?

22:29.528 --> 22:30.327
What is it?

22:30.528 --> 22:32.088
- Uh, it's about Jimmy.
- What about him?

22:32.288 --> 22:34.728
He's proving very useful, sir, and...

22:36.328 --> 22:38.048
Well, sir, he's confessed to me
an interest

22:38.248 --> 22:39.687
in becoming a police officer,
so I thought that I --

22:39.887 --> 22:40.768
I'll stop you right there, Crabtree.

22:40.968 --> 22:42.328
Sir, he's got genuine ability.

22:42.528 --> 22:43.687
I don't doubt he's a smart lad.

22:43.888 --> 22:45.128
He's probably got a better head
on his shoulders

22:45.327 --> 22:46.127
than most of this lot
around here.

22:46.328 --> 22:48.327
Well, then why not g--
Why not give him a chance?

22:48.527 --> 22:50.608
Because I can't change
the world.

22:50.808 --> 22:52.328
I wish I could.

22:54.288 --> 22:55.928
Yes, sir.

23:00.769 --> 23:03.127
A doctor from Port Credit
was found three months ago

23:03.327 --> 23:05.128
with his throat ripped out.

23:06.566 --> 23:07.968
It was assumed to have been
a bear attack.

23:08.168 --> 23:10.007
Though it could just as easily have been
a wolf.

23:11.127 --> 23:13.847
Then in August, a local alderman
was found outside of Galt.

23:14.048 --> 23:16.647
His throat
had also been ripped out.

23:17.688 --> 23:19.288
Wild dogs were thought
to have been responsible.

23:19.488 --> 23:22.408
And then, finally, a Newcastle man
was found in his backyard.

23:22.607 --> 23:24.327
- And his throat was torn out.
- Precisely.

23:24.527 --> 23:26.527
- What profession?
- Lawyer.

23:27.087 --> 23:28.807
These three and Merrill Hardy.

23:29.007 --> 23:30.888
All killed in the same manner.

23:31.088 --> 23:32.207
All toffs.

23:32.408 --> 23:34.047
There's one more connection, sir.

23:34.248 --> 23:36.727
All of these murders took place
under the full moon.

23:36.927 --> 23:38.687
It's still a full moon tonight.

23:38.887 --> 23:39.687
Bloody hell.

23:39.886 --> 23:41.687
Then we'd better find out
where he's going to strike next,

23:41.888 --> 23:42.967
hadn't we?

23:46.168 --> 23:48.127
Sir, I made a few inquiries,

23:48.327 --> 23:50.647
and I found several connections
between the victims.

23:52.247 --> 23:53.967
These two men
went to university together

23:54.167 --> 23:56.007
but didn't get on very well.

23:56.206 --> 23:59.888
Um, these three all invested
in the same oil-drilling project

24:00.087 --> 24:02.447
in Pennsylvania,
which didn't pan out.

24:02.646 --> 24:04.887
And this man was a member
of the same gun club

24:05.087 --> 24:06.406
as Merrill Hardy at one point.

24:07.046 --> 24:09.167
Gun club?
Which gun club?

24:09.926 --> 24:11.567
The Radcliffe Sportsman's Club.

24:12.207 --> 24:14.887
Jacob Summers is a member
of that club.

24:15.647 --> 24:17.528
His wife said
he would be working late.

24:18.726 --> 24:20.767
Mr. Summers?

24:21.607 --> 24:24.567
That's odd.
It's completely dark.

24:24.767 --> 24:26.127
Mr. Summers?

24:29.126 --> 24:31.327
There's something wrong
with the lights.

24:32.206 --> 24:34.767
Sir, what's this?

24:36.525 --> 24:39.527
Shotgun blast, I'd say.

24:39.727 --> 24:41.127
Hello?

24:55.567 --> 24:59.845
I think we can safely eliminate
Mr. Summers as a suspect.

25:06.006 --> 25:07.527
Three shells spent.

25:07.727 --> 25:09.206
One through the door panel.

25:09.406 --> 25:10.726
The other two through the glass.

25:10.927 --> 25:12.326
He must have been
sitting here in the dark

25:12.527 --> 25:13.806
with his finger on the trigger.

25:14.005 --> 25:15.727
As though he was anticipating
an attack.

25:15.926 --> 25:17.325
- Mm.
- Just like Merrill Hardy.

25:17.526 --> 25:18.526
Sir.

25:19.206 --> 25:21.247
You may want to take a look
at this.

25:21.447 --> 25:23.126
The victim is in the picture.

25:23.326 --> 25:25.287
So, too, is Merrill Hardy.

25:33.326 --> 25:35.286
Not just Mr. Hardy, George.

25:35.846 --> 25:38.327
All five victims
are in this photograph.

25:38.526 --> 25:40.006
A hunting party.

25:40.205 --> 25:41.647
But who's the sixth fella?

25:41.846 --> 25:44.086
There's something familiar
about his face.

25:45.486 --> 25:47.445
Well, we'll talk tomorrow.

25:47.647 --> 25:49.326
Detective.

25:50.445 --> 25:52.726
He was with Mr. Summers
at the gun club.

25:52.926 --> 25:56.046
George, see if anyone
at the gun club can identify him.

25:56.246 --> 25:56.806
Sir.

25:57.006 --> 25:58.125
Seems we need to find out
a bit more

25:58.326 --> 26:00.725
about this little hunting party,
me old mucker.

26:00.925 --> 26:02.326
Indeed, sir.

26:02.525 --> 26:06.166
I'm sorry.
I don't... recognize him.

26:07.525 --> 26:10.006
I don't recognize any of them.

26:10.205 --> 26:13.405
Except Jake and...

26:13.606 --> 26:15.806
Merrill, of course.

26:16.525 --> 26:19.326
Mrs. Hardy, do you have any idea
where or when

26:19.525 --> 26:22.005
this photograph
might have been taken?

26:26.086 --> 26:28.526
Merrill's scarf.

26:28.726 --> 26:31.246
I knit it for his birthday.

26:31.445 --> 26:33.166
Last year.

26:35.005 --> 26:37.525
Where did he hunt last fall?

26:38.725 --> 26:42.526
I believe
it was out of Muskoka Lodge.

26:43.244 --> 26:48.125
I remember he came back
and he was very... subdued.

26:48.925 --> 26:51.166
Ill-tempered, really.

26:52.125 --> 26:54.485
We quarreled about it.

27:01.325 --> 27:02.725
Ah. Sir.

27:02.925 --> 27:05.045
We're still trying to determine
this gentleman's identity,

27:05.246 --> 27:06.525
but it's beginning to prove difficult.

27:06.724 --> 27:07.886
We know he's not a member
of the club,

27:08.085 --> 27:09.925
so most likely
he was Mr. Summers' guest.

27:10.125 --> 27:11.765
But then,
as far as pinpointing a name...

27:11.965 --> 27:13.565
I think I can help
narrow things down, George.

27:13.765 --> 27:16.164
- How's that?
- Telephone the Muskoka Lodge

27:16.365 --> 27:18.686
and get a list of every guest
that stayed there last fall.

27:18.886 --> 27:20.724
Compare that to the guest list
at the gun club.

27:20.925 --> 27:21.725
Right away, sir.

27:21.925 --> 27:25.325
Oh, also, Dr. Ogden
is here to see you.

27:28.325 --> 27:30.125
Dr. Ogden.

27:30.324 --> 27:31.685
What brings you here?

27:31.886 --> 27:34.925
I was conducting my postmortem
on Mr. Summers when I discovered

27:35.125 --> 27:36.724
something I felt
you should be made aware of.

27:36.925 --> 27:38.485
- What is it?
- I discovered this

27:38.685 --> 27:41.405
embedded in Mr. Summers'
fourth vertebra.

27:41.606 --> 27:43.324
The lower-right cuspid
of a canine.

27:43.524 --> 27:46.524
I suspect, given the size,
it belongs to a wolf.

27:47.164 --> 27:49.565
Which would seem to confirm
the inspector's theory

27:49.764 --> 27:51.163
of a wolf under a man's control.

27:51.365 --> 27:53.125
Actually, I don't think so.

27:53.324 --> 27:55.684
Teeth, especially healthy teeth,
don't just break off

27:55.884 --> 27:58.925
when ripping through flesh,
which made me curious.

27:59.565 --> 28:01.564
So I inspected the tooth
more closely,

28:01.765 --> 28:04.044
and I discovered
a straight groove

28:04.245 --> 28:06.124
running right through the center of the
breakage point.

28:06.325 --> 28:08.526
As though the tooth
has been drilled through.

28:08.725 --> 28:09.604
Exactly.

28:10.924 --> 28:14.524
Well, I thought you'd want to know
about it straightaway.

28:21.365 --> 28:23.804
William, we can't do this.

28:24.004 --> 28:25.925
We're both involved.

28:26.124 --> 28:26.924
William?

28:27.523 --> 28:28.724
William?

28:29.884 --> 28:30.724
I'm sorry.

28:30.924 --> 28:32.724
My mind was elsewhere.

28:32.924 --> 28:34.484
Thank you, Doctor.

28:34.685 --> 28:36.764
You're welcome, Detective.

28:48.685 --> 28:51.644
Enid, I'm afraid you're right.

28:52.204 --> 28:54.004
I don't think my feelings
for Dr. Ogden

28:54.203 --> 28:56.724
will be dispelled anytime soon.

28:58.525 --> 29:00.523
I see.

29:04.323 --> 29:07.204
But you and Alwyn
have come to mean so much to me.

29:07.404 --> 29:08.964
And you to us.

29:11.445 --> 29:12.883
I confess that I was hoping

29:13.084 --> 29:15.324
you would come
to a different decision.

29:18.124 --> 29:22.323
I never meant to cause
either of you any pain.

29:23.003 --> 29:25.165
I know.

29:27.083 --> 29:29.924
But I think it's best
that you go.

29:39.563 --> 29:41.203
So, this is it, then?

29:43.204 --> 29:45.564
What more could there be?

30:02.963 --> 30:05.324
Goodbye, William.

30:11.042 --> 30:13.723
Goodbye, Enid.

30:22.683 --> 30:24.522
Mother, are you all right?

30:24.722 --> 30:26.883
Come.

30:27.083 --> 30:29.562
Come sit with me awhile.

30:31.042 --> 30:34.522
There's something
we need to talk about.

30:35.684 --> 30:37.323
The tooth was machined, you say?

30:37.523 --> 30:38.563
But why?

30:38.763 --> 30:40.723
So it could be bolted
to some form of device.

30:40.922 --> 30:43.282
I believe that's how the killer
is ripping the throats out.

30:43.483 --> 30:45.124
To create the impression
of a wolf.

30:45.323 --> 30:46.323
Bloody devilish.

30:46.523 --> 30:47.922
Sir, the man in the photo,

30:48.122 --> 30:49.643
we have a name for him --
Frank Jenson.

30:49.843 --> 30:50.642
Very good, George.

30:50.843 --> 30:52.322
Murdoch, keep your wits
about you.

30:52.523 --> 30:53.842
This Jenson
may be another victim,

30:54.043 --> 30:56.363
but he could just as easily
be the killer.

30:56.562 --> 30:58.162
Yes, sir.

31:04.242 --> 31:05.922
Be prepared for anything, George.

31:06.123 --> 31:08.002
Sir.

31:11.522 --> 31:12.963
Police!

31:13.763 --> 31:15.523
Mr. Jenson?

31:16.322 --> 31:17.883
Frank Jenson?

31:43.922 --> 31:45.443
Mr. Jenson.

31:52.962 --> 31:54.322
Put down the gun, Mr. Jenson.

31:56.802 --> 31:58.603
Are you all right?

32:00.321 --> 32:01.482
It's impossible.

32:02.522 --> 32:03.682
Where did he go?

32:09.242 --> 32:10.282
We'll never catch him now.

32:10.481 --> 32:12.402
He's got too much
of a head start.

32:12.603 --> 32:14.481
We'll need Jimmy again.

32:46.801 --> 32:47.761
He went in there.

32:47.961 --> 32:49.522
The sewers again.

32:49.721 --> 32:51.361
Can you track him?

32:51.561 --> 32:53.442
I'll try.

33:33.841 --> 33:35.641
- What is it?
- Shh.

33:38.601 --> 33:40.440
Something's moving.

33:41.520 --> 33:43.561
- I don't hear anything.
- No.

33:43.760 --> 33:45.921
Something's in here with us.

33:58.680 --> 34:00.921
Sir! Sir!

34:08.000 --> 34:09.880
Sir.
Are you all right?

34:10.081 --> 34:11.760
He had me by the throat.

34:11.958 --> 34:12.920
It didn't bite?

34:13.121 --> 34:14.320
I don't know.

34:14.521 --> 34:17.880
He had me and...
just released me.

34:18.081 --> 34:19.440
Jimmy, are you all right?

34:19.639 --> 34:20.440
Fine.

34:20.639 --> 34:22.159
He went this way.

34:22.920 --> 34:26.001
Sir, we came down here
looking for a man, but what I saw --

34:26.201 --> 34:27.121
That was a wolf.

34:27.320 --> 34:28.719
Not a wolf, George.

34:28.920 --> 34:29.920
A wolf would have killed me.

34:30.120 --> 34:32.199
He went out.

34:48.599 --> 34:51.918
Sir, this is the sewer outlet
near the Jamison Foundry.

34:52.120 --> 34:54.639
This would seem to confirm
that he's using the sewers

34:54.840 --> 34:56.760
to access different parts
of the city.

34:56.960 --> 34:59.201
So what should we do now?
Keep tracking him?

34:59.401 --> 35:00.799
No.

35:01.320 --> 35:04.520
I think I know of a quicker route
to finding our killer.

35:05.399 --> 35:08.640
What happened
on that hunting trip, Mr. Jenson?

35:09.839 --> 35:11.320
Don't feel like talking?

35:11.880 --> 35:14.399
Well, sunshine, let me remind you --
Whatever did happen

35:14.600 --> 35:17.520
brought the wrath of hell down
on every man that was with you.

35:17.720 --> 35:19.120
Perhaps you should tell us.

35:19.320 --> 35:22.120
Unless you want to take
your chances the next full moon.

35:26.440 --> 35:28.079
It was an accident.

35:28.639 --> 35:30.040
What was?

35:30.520 --> 35:31.760
It was Jake
who pulled the trigger,

35:31.959 --> 35:33.600
but it wasn't his fault.

35:33.800 --> 35:35.440
It was no one's fault.

35:35.639 --> 35:36.999
We thought it was some animal.

35:37.199 --> 35:38.880
But it wasn't.

35:39.520 --> 35:42.480
Who was shot, Mr. Jenson?

35:43.480 --> 35:45.200
Our guide.

35:46.280 --> 35:48.320
An Indian. I don't --
I don't know his name.

35:48.959 --> 35:51.199
He hit him square in the chest.
There was nothing to be done.

35:52.840 --> 35:56.360
So he died.
Then what happened?

35:57.520 --> 35:58.919
He didn't exactly die.

35:59.119 --> 36:02.200
What do you mean,
"didn't exactly die"?

36:02.399 --> 36:04.519
No, but he was going to.
It was clear.

36:04.719 --> 36:06.320
He had a chest wound,
for God's sake.

36:07.120 --> 36:09.078
- What did you do?
- What -- What could we do?

36:09.280 --> 36:11.719
- The -- The sun was setting.
- You didn't carry him out?

36:12.879 --> 36:14.919
You left him to die -- alone?

36:15.800 --> 36:17.919
We buried him in branches
and leaves.

36:20.280 --> 36:22.480
But he couldn't have lived.

36:22.679 --> 36:23.919
He couldn't have.

36:24.119 --> 36:26.519
Clearly, the man they shot survived.

36:26.719 --> 36:28.719
And now he's seeking
the bloodiest revenge imaginable.

36:28.919 --> 36:30.918
But, sir, whatever attacked us
was not a man.

36:31.119 --> 36:31.959
It was a wolf.

36:32.158 --> 36:33.519
- Or at least some sort of --
- George.

36:33.720 --> 36:36.199
It was a man dressed as a wolf.

36:36.399 --> 36:37.519
Why would he do that?

36:37.719 --> 36:39.079
Perhaps he was
a form of lycanthrope

36:39.280 --> 36:41.479
and the wolf held
some psychological meaning for him.

36:42.199 --> 36:44.918
Actually, sir,
I think he may be a shaman.

36:45.119 --> 36:45.919
A shaman?

36:46.119 --> 36:47.159
We had one in our village.

36:47.359 --> 36:48.638
And sometimes when he danced,

36:48.839 --> 36:51.318
he wore the head
and the skin of a wolf.

36:51.519 --> 36:52.760
Sounds like
what you're describing.

36:52.960 --> 36:53.759
It does.

36:53.958 --> 36:56.319
But what would a shaman be doing working
as a hunting guide?

36:57.359 --> 36:59.719
The missionaries put an end
to the shaman.

36:59.919 --> 37:03.118
Now we have doctors
and the good Lord Jesus.

37:03.319 --> 37:05.359
So this shaman
goes from being a high priest

37:05.559 --> 37:07.319
to a lackey for a bunch
of country-club fat cats.

37:07.518 --> 37:08.758
Who care so little for him,

37:08.958 --> 37:10.399
they leave him to die
in the cold and dark.

37:10.599 --> 37:12.318
And can't even remember
his name.

37:12.518 --> 37:14.959
Can't say I blame him
for tearing their throats out.

37:15.159 --> 37:17.879
But he's killed five men.
And the law is the law.

37:18.078 --> 37:19.960
George, contact
the Muskoka Lodge.

37:20.159 --> 37:21.558
See if anyone there
remembers this man.

37:21.759 --> 37:23.119
Sir.

37:25.757 --> 37:28.118
Now, how do you propose
we find him?

37:30.838 --> 37:34.318
This is a map of the sewer lines
that run beneath the city.

37:34.518 --> 37:36.599
This is where he entered
the system,

37:36.799 --> 37:38.558
near Frank Jensen's house.

37:38.758 --> 37:41.558
This is where
the old Jamison Foundry is...

37:41.759 --> 37:43.478
- ...where Mr. Hardy was found.
- Bloody hell, Murdoch.

37:43.679 --> 37:44.998
There must be a hundred miles
of sewer lines.

37:45.198 --> 37:46.919
- He could be anywhere.
- Not anywhere, sir.

37:47.119 --> 37:49.559
You see, he can only travel
these main lines.

37:49.758 --> 37:52.999
So if we post men at these
main entrances and intersections,

37:53.198 --> 37:54.558
he'll be trapped down there.

38:02.918 --> 38:04.639
- Sir.
- What is it?

38:04.838 --> 38:06.398
There's a light, sir.

38:07.078 --> 38:08.758
Turn off the lamp.

38:23.917 --> 38:25.397
This must be his lair.

38:25.598 --> 38:27.638
So where is he?

38:30.918 --> 38:32.438
His bedding is still warm.

38:32.637 --> 38:34.518
Probably heard us coming.

38:35.198 --> 38:36.199
Sir.

38:39.919 --> 38:41.957
This must be what he used.

38:42.517 --> 38:44.597
Similar to a bear trap.

38:55.517 --> 38:56.918
That would go
through a man's throat

38:57.118 --> 38:59.519
like a knife through butter.

39:08.278 --> 39:09.877
We know who you are.

39:10.437 --> 39:12.237
We know what's happened to you.

39:12.437 --> 39:14.237
It's all over.

39:18.277 --> 39:20.078
He's got a knife, sir.

39:24.837 --> 39:26.837
Frank Jenson is in jail.

39:27.037 --> 39:30.358
Let justice take its course.
Surrender yourself peacefully.

39:30.557 --> 39:32.717
You're up against
armed officers.

39:34.797 --> 39:36.157
Stand down!

39:37.717 --> 39:39.237
Stand down!

39:45.157 --> 39:47.917
George!
George, get help now!

39:48.117 --> 39:51.157
Shh. Don't speak.
Save your strength.

39:55.477 --> 39:56.517
Jimmy, he wants you.

40:02.597 --> 40:04.716
Maheengun.

40:22.637 --> 40:24.277
What did he say?

40:24.477 --> 40:25.277
Maheengun.

40:25.477 --> 40:26.837
What does that mean?

40:27.037 --> 40:30.317
It's an Ojibwa word for "wolf."

40:32.036 --> 40:34.717
I think that was his real name, sir.

40:43.796 --> 40:46.517
The perfect tool
for a murderous lycanthrope.

40:46.717 --> 40:48.116
Would that be
your diagnosis, then?

40:48.316 --> 40:51.717
No. He was most likely suffering
from some kind of psychosis.

40:51.916 --> 40:54.717
He adopted the wolf motif
to reclaim his identity

40:54.916 --> 40:56.798
and terrify his victims.

40:56.997 --> 40:58.676
I imagine, uh, it worked.

40:58.876 --> 41:00.437
What did the full moon
have to do with it?

41:00.637 --> 41:01.916
Poetic justice.

41:02.116 --> 41:03.317
They left him to die
on a full moon.

41:03.517 --> 41:05.916
The man clearly had a flair
for the dramatic.

41:06.117 --> 41:08.236
Yes, he did.
Right to the bloody end.

41:08.796 --> 41:11.276
What I don't understand
is why he came at us like that.

41:11.475 --> 41:13.116
He must have known
we would shoot him down.

41:13.317 --> 41:14.717
Perhaps that's why he did it.

41:14.916 --> 41:17.116
After all, what did he
really have to live for?

41:17.316 --> 41:18.597
He knew he was facing the noose.

41:18.796 --> 41:20.076
Furthermore,
with Jenson arrested,

41:20.276 --> 41:21.996
he'd done what he set out to do.

41:22.196 --> 41:24.515
His desire for revenge
gave him the strength to live.

41:24.716 --> 41:27.197
- Now, with that gone...
- Yes, I suppose.

41:27.396 --> 41:29.795
Still, hell of a thing.

41:29.996 --> 41:31.916
I've never killed a man
like that before.

41:32.116 --> 41:34.076
- But, sir, the regiment.
- Oh, that's different.

41:34.276 --> 41:36.876
You very rarely
come face-to-face.

41:37.396 --> 41:40.117
Last night, I looked this man in the eye
as I pulled the trigger.

41:40.316 --> 41:43.636
Well, if it's any consolation,
you most likely saved my life.

41:43.836 --> 41:46.195
Oh, it's all water
under the bridge now.

41:46.995 --> 41:48.835
Dr. Roberts,
thank you very much.

41:49.036 --> 41:51.196
Your insights
are most appreciated.

41:51.395 --> 41:53.916
Now, if you'll excuse me,
I have someplace I need to be.

41:54.117 --> 41:55.635
As do I.

41:58.596 --> 41:59.635
What's this, then?

41:59.836 --> 42:00.755
My card.

42:00.956 --> 42:04.716
Should you feel the need
to discuss matters, give me a call.

42:05.315 --> 42:06.716
I don't think
there's anything wrong with me

42:06.916 --> 42:09.634
that a couple of whiskeys
won't sort out, Doctor.

42:09.835 --> 42:11.555
As you wish.

42:21.835 --> 42:22.835
Jimmy.

42:23.035 --> 42:24.156
You off, then?

42:24.355 --> 42:25.516
Back to the stables.

42:26.355 --> 42:28.035
Well, it was a pleasure
working with you.

42:28.235 --> 42:29.155
But, you know, in my opinion,

42:29.355 --> 42:31.116
the constabulary
are wasting your talents.

42:31.315 --> 42:33.635
Well, there's no changing
the world, George.

42:33.836 --> 42:35.516
Well, maybe not.

42:35.715 --> 42:36.915
But this might help you.

42:37.115 --> 42:37.915
What's this?

42:38.115 --> 42:40.076
This is a friend of mine
who works at the Pinkertons.

42:40.276 --> 42:42.115
I told him about you.
He's very keen.

42:42.315 --> 42:44.276
You should go to the local office
and ask for him.

42:45.356 --> 42:46.315
I'll think about it.

42:46.514 --> 42:48.115
You do that.

43:03.075 --> 43:04.675
Master Alwyn.

43:04.875 --> 43:06.876
Hello, Mr. Murdoch.

43:07.076 --> 43:09.515
I don't know where my mother is.

43:09.714 --> 43:11.316
Oh, that's all right.

43:11.515 --> 43:13.675
Actually, I'm here to see you.

43:14.355 --> 43:17.755
Really? Mother said you
wouldn't be coming by anymore.

43:22.715 --> 43:23.915
She's right.

43:24.115 --> 43:26.115
I won't be.

43:26.314 --> 43:28.715
So I brought this for you.

43:31.195 --> 43:32.914
"From the Earth to the Moon."

43:33.115 --> 43:34.115
Mm.

43:34.315 --> 43:35.794
It's about
a group of adventurers

43:35.994 --> 43:38.354
who build a cannon
that shoots them to the moon.

43:38.555 --> 43:40.755
Is that even possible?

43:41.355 --> 43:42.955
Well, it's a story.

43:43.154 --> 43:45.794
I suppose anything is possible
in stories.

43:48.115 --> 43:54.314
But if you could build something
that could push you faster

43:54.515 --> 43:57.276
than the earth's gravity
pulls you down...

43:58.274 --> 44:01.475
...you could go faster,
faster, faster,

44:01.674 --> 44:03.995
until you reach escape velocity,

44:04.195 --> 44:07.874
and then the moon, that's just
the beginning of your journey.

44:08.074 --> 44:09.114
That could work?

44:09.714 --> 44:10.515
Theoretically.

44:10.715 --> 44:14.874
Maybe not in my lifetime,
but quite possibly in yours.

44:19.554 --> 44:22.234
"William Henry Murdoch."

44:22.434 --> 44:25.634
It was my favorite book
when I was a boy.

44:26.834 --> 44:28.474
Thank you, Mr. Murdoch.

44:29.314 --> 44:31.514
You're very welcome.

44:35.914 --> 44:37.874
Mr. Murdoch?

44:38.674 --> 44:40.475
Can I still come and see you?

44:42.994 --> 44:44.074
Anytime, Alwyn.

44:45.354 --> 44:47.354
Anytime.

